body:
## Bug

`resolveContextWindowTokens()` in `scripts/lib/transcript-context.js` detects a large context window only via:
1. an explicit `ECC_CONTEXT_WINDOW_TOKENS` / `CLAUDE_CODE_AUTO_COMPACT_WINDOW` env override (added in #2290), or
2. a `[1m]` marker in the model id, or
3. the observed token count already exceeding 200k.

A model whose id carries none of these — a large-window model without the `[1m]` suffix, observed with `model: "claude-fable-5"`, and with usage still below 200k — falls through all three checks and is misclassified as a 200k window.

Observed in session: `[StrategicCompact] Context ~187k tokens (93% of 200k window) - consider /compact at the next logical boundary`, while the session's actual reported usage (from the CLI status line) was ~19%. 187k / 0.19 ≈ 984k, i.e. the real window is ~1M — the hook overstated usage by roughly 5x.

This is the same failure class as #2290 (400k Opus models falling through to the 200k default), but the env-override fix from #2290 does not help here unless the user has manually set `CLAUDE_CODE_AUTO_COMPACT_WINDOW`/`ECC_CONTEXT_WINDOW_TOKENS` — and nothing in the hook or its docs prompts a user to do so for a *new* model family. The `[1m]` marker and the "tokens > 200k" heuristic are both static/stale: neither scales to new model ids as Anthropic ships additional model families with large windows.

## Proposed fix

Add a small model-id-prefix → window-size table as a third fallback, checked before the final 200k default, so common large-window model families are recognized without requiring an env var:

```js
// scripts/lib/transcript-context.js
const KNOWN_MODEL_WINDOW_TOKENS = [
  // [id-substring, window-tokens] — checked in order, first match wins
  ['claude-fable-5', 1000000],
  ['claude-mythos-5', 1000000],
  // extend as new large-window model families ship
];

function resolveContextWindowTokens(tokens, model) {
  // ...existing env override and [1m] marker checks...

  if (typeof model === 'string') {
    const known = KNOWN_MODEL_WINDOW_TOKENS.find(([substr]) => model.includes(substr));
    if (known) return known[1];
  }

  if (Number.isFinite(tokens) && tokens > STANDARD_CONTEXT_WINDOW_TOKENS) {
    return LARGE_CONTEXT_WINDOW_TOKENS;
  }

  return STANDARD_CONTEXT_WINDOW_TOKENS;
}
```

Table entries are best-effort and expected to lag new releases, so this doesn't replace the env-override escape hatch — it just removes the "you must know to set an env var for your new model" trap for the common case. Also worth a doc callout (README/CHANGELOG) telling users on unlisted large-window models to set `CLAUDE_CODE_AUTO_COMPACT_WINDOW` explicitly.

## Test note

`tests/lib/transcript-context.test.js` should add a case for a model id that is large-window but carries neither `[1m]` nor exceeds 200k tokens (e.g. `claude-fable-5` at 187k tokens), asserting the window resolves correctly once the model is in the table — and asserting it still falls back to 200k for a genuinely-unknown small-window model at low token counts (no false positives).

## Environment

- ECC 2.0.0
- Claude Code on `claude-fable-5` (Claude 5 family / Mythos-class tier), large context window, no `[1m]` marker in the reported model id
- `CLAUDE_CODE_AUTO_COMPACT_WINDOW` / `ECC_CONTEXT_WINDOW_TOKENS` not set

Related: #2290 (same failure class, different model family — 400k Opus 4.x)
